T1  - UNEMPLOYMENT, PARTIAL INSURANCE, AND THE MULTIPLIER EFFECTS OF GOVERNMENT SPENDING
AU  - Givens, Gregory E.
Y1  - 2022/05/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12560
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 571
EP  - 599
VL  - 63
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12560
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract I interpret evidence on government spending multipliers using a model in which workers are not fully insured against job loss. Government consumption affects aggregate spending along two margins : (i) an intensive margin owing to a fall in household wealth and (ii) an extensive margin that accounts for growth in the workforce. At insurance levels below a certain threshold, the positive effects of (ii) dominate the negative effects of (i), leading to multipliers for private consumption and output that exceed zero and one. Similar results appear in a quantitative model scaled to match microestimates on the consumption cost of unemployment.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - NETWORK EFFECTS AND SWITCHING COSTS IN THE U.S. WIRELESS INDUSTRY
AU  - Weiergraeber, Stefan
Y1  - 2022/05/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12543
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 601
EP  - 630
VL  - 63
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12543
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract I estimate a model of dynamic consumer behavior to disentangle switching costs and network effects in the U.S. wireless industry. A detailed panel on market shares and churn rates, disaggregated by demographic consumer types and local markets, allows me to separately identify preference heterogeneity, switching costs, and a localized direct network effect. My switching cost estimates range from USD 47 to USD 178. The average willingness-to-pay for a 15 percentage point increase in a carrier's market share is USD 8.50 per month. Finally, I show that ignoring either one of the effects results in substantial errors when simulating counterfactuals.
ER  - 

