T1  - THE FRIEDMAN RULE: EXPERIMENTAL EVIDENCE
AU  - Duffy, John
AU  - Puzzello, Daniela
Y1  - 2022/05/01
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12549
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 671
EP  - 698
VL  - 63
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12549
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract We evaluate the Friedman rule for optimal monetary policy in a laboratory economy based on Lagos?Wright (Journal of Economic Theory 145 (2010), 1508?24). We explore two implementations of Friedman's rule: one involving deflationary monetary policy and another where interest is paid on money. We compare the welfare consequences of the Friedman rule with two other policies: a constant money supply regime and a regime where the money supply grows at a constant k%. Counter to theory, we find that the Friedman rule is not welfare-improving, performing no better than the constant money regime. By one welfare measure, the k% money growth rate regime performs best.
ER  - 

